We found that nycthemeral rhythm of d6 and d7 is different from the rhythm of d1 to d5. For statistical verification, the comparison method was applied to the 93 partitions P âŠ‚ {1...7} of the seven days, that contain at least one element of {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} and at least one element of {6, 7}. So we tested the 93 hypothesis HP : â€œThere is no significant difference between the â€œdayâ€ of partition Pâ€. The comparison method yields p-values smaller than 8.5 Â· 10-11. Bonferroniâ€™s inequality yields an upper bound for the p-value of the hypothesis âˆª HP (â€œThere is at least one of the 93 partitions without significant difference between the nycthemeral rhythms of the â€œdayâ€ of this partitionâ€): P (âˆªHP ) < 93 Â· 8.5 Â· 10-11 <0.05 and thus reject this hypothesis. We accept the alternative hypothesis: â€œthe â€œdayâ€ of all 93 partitions have significant different nycthemeral rhythmsâ€.
